VALUES
(20, 5, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'Let thy fountain be blessed: and rejoice with the wife of thy youth.', 0, 68, 'greek', 'Understanding ''blessed''', 'בָּרוּךְ (baruch, H1288) - blessed, favored. In the Hebrew context, this term conveys a sense of divine favor and prosperity. It suggests that when one’s ''fountain'' (symbolizing life and procreation) is blessed, it implies God’s approval and enrichment in the marital relationship.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1288", "description": "Strong''s number for the term ''blessed''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Let her be as the loving hind and pleasant roe;', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Symbolism of Love', 'The imagery of ''the loving hind and pleasant roe'' evokes tenderness and beauty in marital relationships. This connects to Song of Solomon 2:9, where the beloved is likened to a gazelle, symbolizing grace and desirability. These metaphors illustrate the importance of cherishing one''s spouse and maintaining romantic affection within marriage, reinforcing the call to fidelity and love.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Song of Solomon 2:9", "description": "Emphasizes the beauty and grace in romantic love."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'let her breasts satisfy thee at all times;', 48, 90, 'theology', 'Marital Satisfaction', 'This phrase suggests that marital intimacy is a vital aspect of a healthy relationship, reflecting God''s design for marriage. Many scholars believe this aligns with the doctrine of conjugal love, which teaches that sexual relations within marriage are a gift from God meant to foster unity and joy. This perspective challenges the cultural tendency to view sexuality in isolation from committed relationships.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'and be thou ravished always with her love.', 91, 133, 'question', 'Desire and Commitment', 'What does it mean to be ''ravished'' by love in the context of marriage? How can this passionate commitment inform your own relationships? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper understanding of how fervent love is nurtured and maintained over time, encouraging intentional acts of affection and appreciation.', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'be ravished with a strange woman', 27, 59, 'connection', 'Adultery Warning', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 6:24-25, which warns against the allure of an ''evil woman.'' Both passages highlight the dangers of straying from marital fidelity. The connection underscores the Bible''s consistent teaching on the value of faithfulness in relationships and the destructive consequences of infidelity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 6:24-25", "description": "Warnings against the seductive nature of adultery."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'strange woman', 46, 59, 'theology', 'Concept of Fidelity', 'Many scholars believe this term ''strange woman'' symbolizes not only physical infidelity but also spiritual unfaithfulness. Theological interpretations suggest that turning to ''strange women'' represents a departure from God''s covenant relationship, emphasizing the importance of loyalty to both spouse and God.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on the implications of infidelity in Proverbs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'embrace the bosom of a stranger?', 65, 97, 'question', 'Reflection on Relationships', 'What does the phrase ''embrace the bosom of a stranger'' reveal about the nature of intimacy? In what ways might we be tempted to seek fulfillment outside of our committed relationships, and how does this challenge our understanding of love and loyalty?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'my son', 19, 25, 'greek', 'Addressing Authority', 'Ἰερεμίας (Jeremias, G2419) - Jeremiah, the prophet, often addressed his audience similarly, emphasizing the importance of wisdom in guiding one''s life choices. The familial address here reflects a mentor''s role in teaching and cautioning against pitfalls.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2419", "description": "Strong''s number for the term associated with authority and teaching."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the ways of man are before the eyes of the Lord', 4, 51, 'connection', 'God''s Omniscience', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 139:2, where it states, ''You know when I sit and when I rise; you perceive my thoughts from afar.'' Both passages affirm God''s awareness of human actions and thoughts, highlighting His omniscience. This connection emphasizes that nothing is hidden from God, which serves as a reminder of accountability for our actions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 139:2", "description": "A passage highlighting God''s knowledge of our actions and thoughts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the Lord, and he pondereth all his goings', 43, 84, 'theology', 'Divine Reflection', 'This passage suggests that God not only observes our actions but also carefully considers our paths. Many scholars believe this reflects the theological concept of divine providence, where God actively participates in guiding human lives. It underscores the importance of seeking God''s guidance in our decisions, as He is intimately involved in our journey.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'he pondereth all his goings', 57, 84, 'greek', 'Pondereth Meaning', 'דָּרַךְ (darakh, H1869) - to tread, walk, or go. This word indicates not just the physical act of walking but also metaphorically refers to one''s manner of life or conduct. Understanding this term enriches our comprehension of how God is involved in every aspect of our journey.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1869", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the ways of man are before the eyes of the Lord', 4, 51, 'question', 'Living with Accountability', 'How does the knowledge that ''the ways of man are before the eyes of the Lord'' affect your daily choices? Consider how this awareness might inspire you to align your actions more closely with God''s desires.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'His own iniquities shall take the wicked himself', 0, 48, 'connection', 'Iniquity''s Consequences', 'This phrase echoes the principle found in Galatians 6:7, which states, ''For whatever one sows, that will he also reap.'' Both passages highlight the inevitable consequence of one''s actions, particularly the destructive nature of sin. This connection emphasizes that wickedness leads to self-destruction, aligning with the broader biblical theme of accountability for one''s choices.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:7", "description": "Highlights the principle of reaping what one sows."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'he shall be holden with the cords of his sins', 54, 99, 'greek', 'Cords of Sin', 'עָבוֹת (avot, H5688) - cords, bindings, ties. This Hebrew word signifies a strong connection to something that binds or holds fast. In the context of sin, it suggests that one''s transgressions can ensnare and restrict freedom, illustrating the entrapment that comes from indulging in wrongdoing.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5688", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'His own iniquities shall take the wicked himself', 0, 48, 'theology', 'Nature of Sin', 'Many scholars believe this verse encapsulates the biblical doctrine of sin''s self-destructive nature. It suggests that sin ultimately causes harm not only to the sinner''s relationship with God but also to their well-being and community. This aligns with the broader Christian teaching that sin leads to spiritual death and separation from divine grace.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the self-destructive nature of sin."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'he shall', 54, 62, 'question', 'Value of Wisdom', 'What does it mean to die without instruction, and how does this relate to the importance of seeking wisdom? Reflect on the consequences of ignoring guidance and the role of wisdom in leading a fruitful life. How can we ensure we are not caught in our own iniquities?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'He shall die without instruction;', 0, 33, 'connection', 'Death Without Guidance', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Hosea 4:6, which states, ''My people are destroyed for lack of knowledge.'' Both passages highlight the grave consequences of ignoring divine instruction. The connection underscores the importance of seeking wisdom and understanding to avoid spiritual demise.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hosea 4:6", "description": "Highlights the importance of knowledge in spiritual life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'in the greatness of his folly', 38, 67, 'theology', 'Consequences of Folly', 'This passage suggests that folly leads to destruction, a common theme in Proverbs. Many scholars believe that folly is not just a lack of wisdom but a moral failing that results in separation from God. This underscores the necessity of divine guidance and the peril of choosing one''s own path over God’s wisdom.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'He shall die without instruction;', 0, 33, 'question', 'Value of Instruction', 'What does it mean to you personally to die ''without instruction''? How might this understanding impact the way you seek wisdom in your daily decisions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'and in the greatness of his folly he shall go astray.', 34, 87, 'greek', 'Understanding Folly', 'ἀφροσύνη (aphrosynē, G878) - folly, foolishness. This Greek term conveys a profound lack of understanding and insight, suggesting that folly is not merely an absence of knowledge but an active choice to reject wisdom. Understanding this term enriches our grasp of the consequences of ignoring God''s guidance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G878", "description": "Strong''s number for folly in the New Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'if thou be surety for thy friend', 8, 40, 'connection', 'Surety in Scripture', 'The concept of being a surety or guarantor appears in several places in Scripture, notably in Proverbs 11:15, which warns that ''he who is surety for a stranger will suffer for it.'' This connection highlights the potential dangers of putting oneself in a position of financial or personal responsibility for others without careful consideration, emphasizing wisdom in relationships.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 11:15", "description": "Related warning about suretyship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'if thou hast stricken thy hand with a stranger', 42, 88, 'theology', 'Commitment and Responsibility', 'Many scholars believe that striking hands signifies a formal agreement or commitment. This passage suggests a serious caution about entering into agreements or partnerships with those outside one''s close community, reflecting the biblical principle of wisdom in making commitments. It teaches that such actions should be approached with prayerful consideration and discernment.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs Commentary by Matthew Henry", "description": "Discusses the implications of making commitments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'My son', 0, 6, 'question', 'Personal Application', 'What does it mean for you to heed the advice of a mentor or wise figure in your life? How can you apply this wisdom in your decisions about relationships and commitments?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'if thou be surety for thy friend', 8, 40, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Surety''', 'עָבוּר (ʿāḇûr, H5670) - surety, pledge, or guarantee. This term emphasizes the weight of responsibility one takes on when agreeing to back someone else''s obligations, underscoring the need for caution in such commitments.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5670", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Thou art snared with the words of thy mouth, thou art taken with the words of thy mouth.', 0, 88, 'connection', 'Power of Speech', 'This verse connects with James 3:5-6, which highlights how the tongue can cause great destruction, likening it to a small fire setting a forest ablaze. Just as Proverbs warns of the consequences of careless speech, James elaborates on the potential harm that can arise from our words, reminding us of the need for careful and wise communication.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:5-6", "description": "Explains the destructive power of the tongue."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Thou art snared with the words of thy mouth, thou art taken with the words of thy mouth.', 0, 88, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Snared''', 'נָקַשׁ (naqash, H5367) - to ensnare, to trap. The Hebrew term conveys the idea of being caught or entangled, indicating that one''s own words have the power to lead to one''s downfall. This emphasizes the importance of mindfulness in speech, as our own utterances can create situations where we find ourselves trapped.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5367", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''snared''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Thou art snared with the words of thy mouth, thou art taken with the words of thy mouth.', 0, 88, 'theology', 'Theological Implications of Speech', 'This verse suggests that our words hold significant weight in our moral and spiritual lives. Many scholars believe that this reflects a broader theological truth about the power of communication in shaping reality. In Christian teachings, words can create, destroy, bless, or curse, underscoring the responsibility believers have to speak truthfully and lovingly.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 18:21", "description": "Cites the power of life and death in the tongue."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Thou art snared with the words of thy mouth, thou art taken with the words of thy mouth.', 0, 88, 'question', 'Reflecting on Our Speech', 'How can we guard against being ensnared by our own words? This verse prompts us to consider the impact of our speech on our relationships and integrity. What practical steps can we take to ensure our words reflect wisdom and truth, and how can we seek forgiveness when we fail in this area?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'Do this now, my son,', 0, 20, 'question', 'Immediate Action Required', 'What does it mean to act ''now'' in the context of our relationships? How can we apply urgency in reconciling with friends when conflicts arise, as this verse suggests?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'humble thyself,', 94, 109, 'theology', 'Humility in Restoration', 'This passage emphasizes humility as essential for reconciliation. Many scholars believe that humility is a foundational virtue in Christian teaching, reflecting Christ''s own example in Philippians 2:3-4, where believers are encouraged to consider others above themselves.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'deliver thyself,', 25, 41, 'connection', 'Deliverance Themes', 'This theme of ''deliverance'' resonates with other Scriptures, such as Psalm 34:17, which states that the Lord hears the cries of the righteous and delivers them. It reminds us that while we take responsibility for our actions, divine assistance is also a crucial element in our deliverance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 34:17", "description": "The Lord''s faithfulness in delivering those in need."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'make sure thy friend.', 114, 135, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Make Sure''', 'The phrase ''make sure'' can be linked to the Hebrew term ''תִּקֵּן'' (tiqqen, H8610) - to set right, to restore. This emphasizes the act of restoring relationships and ensuring peace, which is a significant aspect of biblical community life.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8610", "description": "Strong''s definition for further study."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Give not sleep to thine eyes,', 0, 29, 'connection', 'Alertness in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes the admonition found in 1 Thessalonians 5:6, where believers are urged to be awake and sober. The connection highlights the importance of spiritual vigilance and discernment, emphasizing that laziness can lead to spiritual danger.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:6", "description": "Encourages spiritual alertness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'nor slumber to thine eyelids.', 30, 59, 'theology', 'Spiritual Diligence', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects the broader biblical theme of diligence versus sloth. The call to avoid slumber symbolizes a need for continuous effort in spiritual pursuits, suggesting that complacency can lead to moral and spiritual decline.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Give not sleep to thine eyes,', 0, 29, 'question', 'Personal Vigilance', 'What practical steps can you take to ensure that you remain spiritually awake and active in your faith journey, as this verse encourages?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'nor slumber to thine eyelids.', 30, 59, 'greek', 'Key Hebrew Term', 'שֵׁנָה (shenah, H8162) - sleep, slumber. This term conveys the idea of both physical sleep and a metaphorical state of spiritual lethargy, underscoring the warning against complacency.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8162", "description": "Hebrew term for sleep."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Deliver thyself as a roe from the hand of the hunter', 0, 52, 'connection', 'Escape from Danger', 'This phrase echoes the urgency found in Psalm 124:7, which states, ''Our soul is escaped as a bird out of the snare of the fowlers.'' Both verses emphasize the need for swift action in times of peril. The imagery of animals escaping from hunters highlights the instinctive response required when faced with spiritual or ethical dilemmas.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 124:7", "description": "Emphasizes the theme of deliverance from danger."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'as a bird from the hand of the fowler', 58, 95, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Birds', 'Birds often symbolize freedom and the soul''s escape from earthly constraints in biblical literature. Many scholars believe this metaphor illustrates God''s desire for believers to seek liberation from sin and temptation, akin to how birds instinctively flee from capture. This notion aligns with the broader Christian teaching of salvation and deliverance through faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of birds as symbols of liberation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Deliver thyself', 0, 15, 'question', 'Personal Responsibility', 'What does it mean for you to ''deliver thyself'' in your own life? Consider the areas where you may need to take initiative and act decisively to avoid spiritual traps or ethical compromises. How does this call to action influence your understanding of personal responsibility in faith?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Go to the ant, thou sluggard;', 0, 29, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Creation', 'This call to observe the ant resonates with other biblical themes emphasizing the wisdom found in creation. For example, Jesus references the natural world in Matthew 6:26, urging people to consider the birds and their provision. Such connections remind us that God’s creation offers lessons about diligence and reliance on Him.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:26", "description": "Jesus teaches about God''s provision through nature."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'consider her ways,', 30, 48, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Consider''', 'The Hebrew word for ''consider'' is חָכַם (chakam, H2449) - to be wise, to be skillful. This suggests that the act of considering is not merely observational but involves engaging with wisdom to apply it in our lives. It highlights the expectation that we should learn from creation actively.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2449", "description": "Strong''s number for the term indicating wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'thou sluggard;', 15, 29, 'theology', 'Diligence vs. Sloth', 'This verse contrasts the diligent nature of the ant with the sluggard, a common biblical archetype representing laziness. Many scholars believe this passage reflects a broader biblical theme that emphasizes the virtue of hard work and the consequences of idleness, as seen in 2 Thessalonians 3:10.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "2 Thessalonians 3:10", "description": "Paul''s teaching on work and responsibility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'consider her ways,', 30, 48, 'question', 'Learning from the Ant', 'What specific qualities of the ant can I apply to my own work ethic and spiritual life? How does recognizing these qualities challenge my current habits of diligence or laziness?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Which having no guide, overseer, or ruler,', 0, 42, 'connection', 'Leadership in Wisdom', 'This verse echoes the sentiment found in Proverbs 29:18, ''Where there is no vision, the people perish.'' Both verses highlight the necessity of guidance in achieving wisdom and productivity. The ant''s ability to thrive without direct oversight serves as a powerful contrast to human laziness, reminding us that we must take initiative in our lives.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 29:18", "description": "Highlights the importance of guidance and vision."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Which having no guide, overseer, or ruler,', 0, 42, 'theology', 'Self-Governance and Responsibility', 'This passage suggests that individuals are called to exercise self-governance and responsibility. Many scholars believe that this reflects the doctrine of personal accountability that is prevalent throughout Scripture, emphasizing that believers are empowered by the Holy Spirit to make wise decisions without constant oversight.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 6:6-8 Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theme of personal responsibility in Proverbs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Which having no guide, overseer, or ruler,', 0, 42, 'greek', 'Guide and Ruler', 'רֹב (rob, H7227) - multitude, chief. The term conveys the idea of a leader or overseer. In the context of this verse, it underscores the ant''s independence in gathering food, illustrating wisdom in preparation without external direction.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7227", "description": "Strong''s entry for the term indicating leadership."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Which having no guide, overseer, or ruler,', 0, 42, 'question', 'Reflecting on Guidance', 'In what areas of your life do you rely too heavily on external guidance? How might you cultivate the wisdom and initiative of the ant to take responsibility for your own actions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'Provideth her meat in the summer, and gathereth her food in the harvest.', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Nature''s Wisdom', 'This verse parallels 2 Thessalonians 3:10, which states, ''For even when we were with you, we gave you this rule: The one who is unwilling to work shall not eat.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of diligent preparation and work as central to a fruitful life. The ant serves as a model for proactive behavior, encouraging believers to avoid laziness and to be responsible stewards of their time and resources.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "2 Thessalonians 3:10", "description": "Emphasizes the necessity of work for sustenance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'Provideth her meat in the summer, and gathereth her food in the harvest.', 0, 72, 'theology', 'Stewardship and Preparation', 'Many scholars believe this passage highlights the theological principle of stewardship, which involves managing resources wisely and preparing for the future. The ant''s behavior serves as a metaphor for the need for foresight and responsibility in one''s life, reflecting God''s expectation for humanity to work diligently and provide for themselves and others. This aligns with the biblical call to be good stewards of God''s creation.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 6, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'in the summer', 19, 32, 'question', 'Seasonal Readiness', 'What does the emphasis on ''summer'' teach us about the importance of timing in our own efforts? How can we apply the principle of seizing opportunities when they arise to our spiritual and personal lives? Reflecting on this can help us recognize the seasons of our lives and the need for proactive engagement during times of abundance.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');